/wiki/Braunau_am_Inn_(district):
Bezirk Braunau am Inn is a district of the state of
Upper Austria in Austria.
/wiki/Braunau_am_Inn: The town is on the lower river Inn below its confluence with the Salzach, where it forms the border with the German state of Bavaria, halfway on the road between the state capital Linz and the Bavarian capital Munich, about 60 km (37 mi) north of Salzburg. Braunau is connected by bridges over the Inn with its Bavarian counterpart Simbach am Inn. A traditional port of entry, all border controls have been abolished since the implementation of the Schengen Agreement by Austria in 1997.
/wiki/Upper_Austria: Upper Austria (German: Oberösterreich [ˈoːbɐˌʔøːstɐʁaɪ̯ç] (listen); Austro-Bavarian: Obaöstarreich; Czech: Horní Rakousy; Slovak: Horné Rakúsko) is one of the nine states or Bundesländer of Austria. Its capital is Linz. Upper Austria borders on Germany and the Czech Republic, as well as on the other Austrian states of Lower Austria, Styria, and Salzburg. With an area of 11,982 km2 (4,626 sq mi) and 1.437 million inhabitants, Upper Austria is the fourth-largest Austrian state by land area and the third-largest by population.

Bezirk Eferding is a district of the state of 
Upper Austria in Austria.
/wiki/Eferding: Eferding is the center of the Eferding basin. The city is 2 km away from the Danube River. It has[clarification needed] in Upper Austria.
/wiki/Freistadt_(district):
Bezirk Freistadt is a district of the state of 
Upper Austria, in central northern Austria.
/wiki/Freistadt: The area surrounding Freistadt came under the dominion of the Bavarian Duchy in the seventh century.
/wiki/Gmunden_(district):
Bezirk Gmunden is a district of the state of 
Upper Austria in Austria.
/wiki/Gmunden: Gmunden ([ˈɡmʊndən] (listen)) is a town in Upper Austria, Austria in the district of Gmunden. It has 13,204 inhabitants (estimates 2016 ). It is much frequented as a health and summer resort, and has a variety of lake, brine, vegetable and pine-cone baths, a hydropathic establishment, inhalation chambers, whey cure, etc. It is also an important centre of the salt industry in Salzkammergut.
/wiki/Grieskirchen_(district):
Bezirk Grieskirchen is a district of the state of 
Upper Austria in Austria.
/wiki/Grieskirchen: Grieskirchen is a town in Austria. It is capital of the Grieskirchen district of Upper Austria, in the Trattnachtal valley. The musicologist Franz Födermayr was born in the town in 1933.
/wiki/Kirchdorf_an_der_Krems_(district):
Bezirk Kirchdorf an der Krems is a district of the state of 
Upper Austria in Austria.
/wiki/Kirchdorf_an_der_Krems: Kirchdorf an der Krems is a town in the Austrian state of Upper Austria on the river Krems, in the district of  Kirchdorf an der Krems. Apparently settled by the year 903,[citation needed] it has 4,104 inhabitants in a relatively small area of 3 km2.
/wiki/Linz-Land: Bezirk Linz-Land is a district of Upper Austria in Austria.
/wiki/Linz: Linz (/lɪnts, lɪnz/, German: [ˈlɪnts]; Czech: Linec) is the third-largest city of Austria and capital and largest city of the state of Upper Austria (German: Oberösterreich). It is in the north centre of Austria, approximately 30 kilometres (19 miles) south of the Czech border, on both sides of the river Danube. The population of the city is 205,726, and that of the Greater Linz conurbation is about 789,811.
/wiki/Perg_(district):
Bezirk Perg is a district of the state of 
Upper Austria in Austria.
/wiki/Perg: Perg is a city in the Austrian state of Upper Austria, capital of the district of the same name.
/wiki/Ried_im_Innkreis_(district):
Bezirk Ried im Innkreis is a district of the state of 
Upper Austria in Austria.
/wiki/Ried_im_Innkreis: Ried im Innkreis is a town in the Austrian state of Upper Austria, approximately 70 km (43 mi) west of Linz and 60 km (37 mi) north of Salzburg. It is the capital of the district of Ried im Innkreis, and it serves as the administrative centre for the Innviertel region.
/wiki/Rohrbach_(district):
Bezirk Rohrbach is a district of the state of 
Upper Austria in Austria.
/wiki/Rohrbach_im_M%C3%BChlkreis: Rohrbach in Oberösterreich was a town and capital of the district of Rohrbach in the Austrian state of Upper Austria. On May 1, 2015 Rohrbach was merged with neighboring community of Berg bei Rohrbach to the municipality Rohrbach-Berg.
/wiki/Sch%C3%A4rding_(district):
Bezirk Schärding is a district of the state of 
Upper Austria in Austria.
/wiki/Sch%C3%A4rding: As of 1 January 2014, it had a population of 4,874.
/wiki/Steyr-Land:
Bezirk Steyr-Land is a district of the state of 
Upper Austria in Austria.
/wiki/Steyr: Steyr (German pronunciation: [ˈʃtaɪ̯ɐ] (listen)) is a statutory city, located in the Austrian federal state of Upper Austria. It is the administrative capital, though not part of Steyr-Land District. Steyr is Austria's 12th most populated town and the 3rd largest town in Upper Austria.
/wiki/Urfahr-Umgebung:
Bezirk Urfahr Umgebung is a district of the state of 
Upper Austria in Austria. It is named after Urfahr, a former city, today a borough of Linz, seat of the district's administration (Bezirkshauptmannschaft).
/wiki/V%C3%B6cklabruck_(district):
Bezirk Vöcklabruck is a district of the state of 
Upper Austria in Austria.
/wiki/V%C3%B6cklabruck: Vöcklabruck's name derives from the River Vöckla which runs through the town, whose name in turn originates from a person's name ('Vechela') and 'Ache', meaning 'flowing water' or 'river'.
/wiki/Wels-Land:
Bezirk Wels-Land is a district of the state of 
Upper Austria in Austria.
/wiki/Wels: Wels (German pronunciation: [vɛls]) is a city in Upper Austria, on the Traun River near Linz. It is the county seat of Wels-Land, and with a population of approximately 60,000, the eighth largest city in Austria.
